item.title: Chapter 1 - Part 1 - Annulus
item.description:
Robot Arm Structure: Each robot arm segment is represented as a straight-line segment with fixed length and zero thickness.
Reachability Region: The main question is determining the totality of points in 3D space that the arm can reach, known as the reachability region.


Annulus: The reachability region of an n-link robot arm is an annulus, which is the region between two concentric circles (2D) or spheres (3D) with different radii. This includes two special cases: a single circle or a disk.
Theorem 1.1: Establishes that the reachability region is an annulus.


Base Case: A 1-link arm reaches points on a circle, which is an annulus.
Induction Step: For an n-link arm, removing the last link gives an (n-1)-link arm with a reachability region as an annulus. Adding the last link extends this region, maintaining the annulus shape.


Outer Radius (r+): The maximum reach of the arm is the sum of the lengths of all links. r+=l1+l2+⋯+lnr+ = l1 + l2 + + lnr+=l1+l2+⋯+ln
Inner Radius (r−): Depends on the lengths of the links and whether they can fully fold back on themselves.
If the sum of lengths of all but the longest link (M) is less than the longest link (L), the inner radius is L−ML - ML−M.
If MMM is greater than or equal to LLL, the inner radius is zero, making the region a disk.

item.title: Chapter 1 - Part 2 - Reaching Angles
item.description:
Key Question: Given an n-link arm and a point p within its reachability annulus ​, what set of joint angles will place the hand at p?
Restated Question: Instead of focusing directly on angles, the problem can be rephrased to find joint positions that align the arm appropriately.


2-Link Arm: The intersection of two circles (one centered at ​ with radius ​ and the other at =p with radius ​) provides the possible positions for ​.
Generic Case: Typically, two distinct points of intersection exist.
Degenerate Cases: Situations with one or infinitely many intersection points.


3-Link Arm: The solution involves solving multiple 2-link problems:
Case 1: p lies on the outer boundary of the annulus ​.
Case 2: p lies on the inner boundary of ​.
Case 3: p remains within ​ throughout the sweep.
n-Link Arm: The "Two Kinks Theorem" states that an n-link arm can reach any point within its reachability region with at most two kinks. This reduces the complexity of solving n-link problems to solving 2-link and 3-link problems.



3D to 2D Reduction: By slicing the 3D reachability region with a plane containing ​ and p, the problem is reduced to solving within this 2D plane.


Interpolation of Angles: Moving continuously between initial and final joint configurations can be achieved by interpolating the joint angles linearly.
Self-Intersection Consideration: Real-world applications must consider the possibility of self-intersecting configurations.

item.title: Chapter 2 - Straight-Line Linkages and the Pantograph
item.description:
Linkages have been used historically in various mechanical devices, with their golden age being the eighteenth century. This period was driven by the needs of the steam engine, where precise straight-line motion was essential to avoid wear and tear on piston rods.

Watt's Linkage: James Watt's invention in 1784 addressed the need for straight-line motion in steam engines. It consists of a 3-bar linkage that ensures the midpoint of a link moves in a nearly straight line. The joints are pinned and can rotate, while the midpoint traces a figure-8 curve, staying on nearly straight sections. This invention was pivotal for steam engine efficiency despite its approximate straight-line motion.

Chebyshev's Linkage: Russian mathematician Pafnuty Chebyshev improved upon Watt's linkage in the 1850s. His linkage, shown at the 1878 World’s Fair, achieved a closer approximation to straight-line motion. Chebyshev's work led to the development of Chebyshev polynomials.

Peaucellier-Lipkin Linkage: In 1864, Charles-Nicolas Peaucellier invented the first linkage that achieved exact straight-line motion. This linkage, also independently discovered by Lipman Lipkin, uses a rhombus configuration to maintain precise linear movement.


The pantograph is a versatile and historically significant linkage that allows for copying drawings at different scales. It consists of four bars forming a parallelogram, where the motion of one joint is scaled by another joint.

Basic Functionality: The pantograph duplicates movements at a scaled ratio, determined by the lengths of its bars. This principle is used in various applications, from enlarging drawings to maintaining electrical contact in trains.

Mathematical Analysis: The analysis of the pantograph's movement involves vectors and scaling factors. For instance, a pantograph with a scale factor of 2 will duplicate the traced curve at twice the size.

Historical and Modern Uses: Historically, pantographs were used for copying and engraving. Notable uses include Thomas Jefferson's polygraph for duplicating correspondence and the chess-playing automaton "The Turk," which used a pantograph to transfer movements from a hidden operator to a visible figure.


Alfred Bray Kempe explored whether a linkage could trace any given algebraic curve, leading to what is now known as Kempe’s Universality Theorem. This theorem states that there exists a linkage capable of tracing any algebraic curve, effectively "signing your name." This discovery highlights the potential complexity and versatility of linkages, although constructing such linkages can be highly intricate and typically nonplanar.
This section of the chapter underscores the mathematical depth and historical significance of linkages, particularly those capable of straight-line motion and scalable copying. The pantograph, with its straightforward yet powerful mechanics, serves as a key example of the practical applications of linkage theory.
item.link: How to fold it\Chapter 2 - Straight-Line Linkages and the Pantograph.html

item.title: Chapter 3 - Protein Folding and Pop-Up Cards
item.description:
In previous chapters, robot-arm polygonal chains and linkages were discussed, where all joints had complete rotational freedom. In this chapter, open polygonal chains with fixed angles at each joint, known as fixed-angle chains, are explored. Despite the fixed angles, motion is still possible in 3D through revolute or dihedral motion, where adjacent links can revolve around the middle link while maintaining the fixed joint angle.

Proteins are long chains of atoms with short side chains, consisting of repeated 3-atom cores of amino acids (NCC). These backbones fold into complex 3D shapes, determined by the sequence of amino acids, leading to a unique native state. Misfoldings can cause diseases, such as Mad Cow disease. Simplifying the complex reality of protein folding, reducing proteins to unit 90°-chains for analysis.

Chemists are interested in the statistical distribution of end-to-end lengths of polymers, including proteins. The maximum span, or maxspan, is the maximum end-to-end distance of a chain. Understanding which configurations of a unit 90°-chain achieve the maxspan is the focus.

The alignment of a chain involves positioning it such that its ends are maximally separated. This requires careful configuration of each link, ensuring they are aligned in a way that maximizes the overall length of the chain.

The Piercing Theorem is introduced, which shows that in certain configurations, a chain's segments can be arranged such that they all pierce through a common segment. This theorem applies to unit 90°-chains, where the chain can be configured into a planar staircase shape, achieving the maximum span.

Pop-up books and cards have seen a resurgence in popularity. The pop-up spinner card, invented in Japan in 1988, is highlighted for its elegant design. The card's construction relies on converting the opening motion into a pop-up effect. The key to understanding its operation is the Unit-90° Theorem. The card design involves cuts, mountain folds, and valley folds, which create a zig-zag chain of creases. When the card is opened, this chain uncurls from a spiral to a planar state, causing the attached diamond frames to spin.


The chapter moves from geometric analysis to computational simulations of protein folding. Folding@Home is a project that uses idle computers to simulate protein folding pathways. An example is the accurate simulation of the 36-amino acid protein, the "villin headpiece," which folds rapidly and is surrounded by water molecules in the simulation.

An unsolved problem in the geometry of fixed-angle chains is whether a unit 90°-chain can lock. A chain is considered locked if it cannot be untangled without passing through itself. The smallest known length ratio for a locked 90°-chain is slightly more than , achieved with a 6-link chain. The question remains whether a unit 90°-chain with a smaller length ratio can lock.

item.title: Chapter 4 - Flat vertex folds
item.description:
Origami folds can be classified into two types: mountain folds and valley folds. When a paper is folded, the resulting crease forms a line. Mountain folds create a peak along the crease, while valley folds create a trough. In traditional origami diagrams, valley folds are indicated by dashed lines and mountain folds by a dash-dot pattern. This section emphasizes that the classification of a fold as a mountain or valley depends on the viewer's perspective; flipping the paper changes the classification of the folds.

Flat folding in origami can be analyzed through the lens of single-vertex folds, where multiple creases converge at a single point. The simplest example involves folding a sheet of paper twice, creating a vertex where four creases meet. Single-vertex flat folds exhibit rich mathematical properties, offering insights into more complex origami structures.

Degree of a Vertex: The degree of a vertex is the number of creases incident to it. A fundamental observation is that a vertex in a flat fold must have an even degree.
Theorem 4.1 (Even Degree): A vertex in a flat folding has an even degree.

This theorem, discovered independently by Jun Maekawa and Jacques Justin, provides a key regularity for flat foldings:

Theorem 4.2 (Maekawa-Justin): If M mountain creases and V valley creases meet at a vertex of a flat folding, then M and V differ by 2: either M=V+2 or V=M+2.
The theorem is validated through various examples, showing that it holds true for different crease patterns. The proof involves analyzing the angles and zig-zag paths created by the folds around the vertex.

This theorem addresses the local minima in the angular arrangement of creases:

Theorem 4.3 (Local Min): In any flat folding, any wedge whose angle is a local minimum must be delimited by one mountain and one valley fold.
This theorem explains why certain crease patterns cannot fold flat, as the local minima force specific configurations of mountain and valley folds.

This theorem provides a complete characterization of single-vertex flat foldability, focusing on the angles formed by the creases:

Theorem 4.4 (Kawasaki-Justin): A set of an even number of creases meeting at a vertex folds flat if, and only if, the alternating sum of the determined wedge angles is zero:


Flat origami involving multiple vertices presents a complex problem. Although each vertex individually satisfies the theorems discussed, determining the flat foldability of the entire pattern is NP-hard, meaning it is computationally intractable. This complexity ensures that the artistic aspect of flat origami remains beyond complete mechanization.

An unsolved problem in origami is determining whether a given map crease pattern can be folded flat. This problem, though seemingly simple, has defied a complete mathematical characterization, highlighting the inherent complexity of flat foldability in practical applications such as map folding.

item.guid: How to fold it/Chapter 4 - Flat vertex folds.md

item.title: Chapter 5 - Fold and One-Cut
item.description:
The Fold and One-Cut Theorem, states that any shape composed of straight-line segments can be obtained through appropriate folding and a single straight cut. This theorem has profound implications for both theoretical and practical applications in mathematics and art.

Statement of the Theorem: Any planar straight-line drawing can be folded such that a single straight cut will produce the drawing. This includes complex shapes and configurations, provided they can be decomposed into straight-line segments.

The proof of the Fold and One-Cut Theorem involves several key steps:

Graph Representation: The shape to be cut is represented as a graph, where the vertices are points of intersection of the straight lines, and the edges are the segments between these points.
MST and Fold Path: The construction of a minimum spanning tree (MST) from the graph, which helps in determining the fold path. The fold path is a sequence of folds that align all the edges of the MST.
Aligning Creases: By aligning the creases according to the fold path, the paper can be folded into a configuration where a single straight cut along a line will intersect all the edges of the MST, thus producing the desired shape.

item.title: Magnetic Micro-Origami
item.description:
Grain coalescence: happen when the mass of two neigh- boring grains differ significantly, the larger grain incorporates the smaller one while the total number of grains is reduced by one.
Heteroepitaxy: Heteroepitaxy is the growth of a crystalline film on a crystalline substrate of a different material.

Hygroscopicity: a physical property of a material, is a measure of how well the material can absorb and release water molecules

Epitaxy: refers to a type of crystal growth or material deposition in which new crystalline layers are formed with one or more well-defined orientations with respect to the crystalline seed layer.





Indium arsenide atoms arriving on the AlAs surface must reduce their interatomic distances to match the lattice of AlAs. Therefore, the InAs film on AlAs is in compressed state. On the other hand, GaAs atoms experience tensile stresses when they form single crystal film on the top of InAs with larger lattice constant. When AlAs sacrificial layer is selectively etched (with selectivity better than 1:1000), the initially com‐ pressed InAs expands and the strained GaAs shrinks resulting in bending and rolling of the pattern of the bilayered film of InAs/GaAs which eventually forms a multiwall tube. For very thin films (a few atomic layers), the 7.5% mismatch strain between InAs and GaAs lattices results in a very small diameter of the tubes (down to 2 nm). Depending on the size of the rectangular pattern the number of turns can change between 1 and 40. The diameter of the tubes can be designed using Formula 1. Here, it is important to note that ferromagnetic films such as single crystalline Fe or antiferromagnetic films such as , , or can be grown epitaxially on top of GaAs.


A concept of using anisotropic properties of composite materials to control rolling direction


(a) Al/Pt film pattern deposited on top of photoresist and (b) the same bilayered film deposited on top of glucose film (images obtained by optical profiler).


First, the 50 μm × 50 μm holes were defined in a PMMA photoresist using exposure of the photoresist to deep UV light through as mask. Thin film of Cu was deposited by sputtering on the Si wafer with (001) orientation. During a lift-off process the Cu film pieces on top of photoresist were removed by ultrasonication of the wafer immersed in acetone. The remaining 50 nm thick Cu squares served as sacrificial layer. Another mask with 20 μm × 50 μm rectangles was used to deposit the trilayered Ti/GaFe/Au and Ti/Ni/Au films. This mask was aligned in such a way that the majority of the area of the rectangular holes in photoresist was on top of the Cu squares and a smaller part on exposed Si. After deposition of the trilayer and the second lift-off process the rectangles remained on top of Cu patches, which were partially attached to Si, as presented in Figure 4(a). During selective etching of the sacrificial Cu underlayer, the films with residual stresses, caused by the grain coalescence, self-rolled, and formed magnetic microtubes with 3–4 turns, diameter of 5–10 μm, and the length of 20 μm Figure 4(b)


Magnetization hysteresis loops of rectangular film patterns 20 μm × 50 μm with Ni layer (black line), micro‐ tubes (red line), and anodized microtubes (blue line). Top part refers to the 0° angle and the bottom to 90° angle of the applied magnetic field


Magnetization hysteresis loops of rectangular film patterns 20 μm × 50 μm with GaFe layer (black line), mi‐ crotubes (red line), and anodized microtubes (blue line). Top part refers to the 0° angle and the bottom to 90° angle of the applied magnetic field.


It is possible to fabricate origami figures with features as small as 2nm.

Adhesion forces, surface tension, or interfacial stresses start playing important roles when the size of the figures decreases below several micrometers.

Taken from introduction: Magnetostrictive and multiferroic materials take a special place among the stimuli-responsive materials, because they couple magnetic, elastic, and electronic properties of the materials.
Taken from surface tension: Self-assembled structures can serve as building blocks for designing mesoscopic metamaterials with interesting responses to electromagnetic radiation in microwave, millimeter wave, and optical ranges


Magnetic films are good candidates for the micro- and nano-origami structures.
Forces:
Surface tension
This force is of primary importance in micro- and nanoscales. The surface tension of evaporating drop of liquid s sufficient to pull the walls of the photolithographically defined thin film patterns together. These patterns typically consist of more rigid areas connected by thinner areas. In some cases, the capillary forces can produce reversible conformations due to swelling and dehydrating of porous structures.
Residual and interfacial stresses
Growth of polycrystaline films may lead to significant residual stresses due to coalescence of grains. The curvature of the films depends on the internal stress level and thickness of the film. According to Equation 1, the smaller origami figures the tinner films must be used. If the tensile stresses in the bilayers are smaller near the substrate than o the film surface, the film released from the substrate tends to bend under and may form wrinkles. Much better control of stresses can be achieved in heteroepitaxial structures.
They used misfit between single crystalline semiconductor films grown epitaxially on top of each other as shown in Figure 1 (I did not understand a thing).
Thermal stresses in thin films provide another way to deform flat patterns after release from the substrate.

Other useful forces
Application of external stresses can be realized by deposition of the films on bent or strained substrates.
Significant stresses in thin films can occur when the films undergo change of crystal structure or are chemically altered.
Controlling direction of self-assembly:
The shape may define the direction. Films with uniform in-plane stresses is proportional to the length of the edge. The bending of longer edges prevails. Rigid parts of the pattern, such as thicker walls of origami can act as constraints. For certain stress gradient level a regular wrinkling is expected rather than bending. Control of rolling directions is easier to achieve in heteroepitaxial structures.
Anisotropic elastic properties in combination with selective anisotropic etching can be used to fabricate variety of three-dimensional structures by depositing film patterns at different angles.
Aligned carbon nanotubes embedded in polymer or magnetic film can control the pitch of the helical structures depending on the angle between the pattern and the direction of the enforcing element as shown in Figure 2.
A sacrificial layer
Vast majority of techniques uses solid sacrificial underlayers to build patterns on top of them.
Requirementes:
The sacrificial layer must form a smooth surface, promote proper growth of the film, and enable patterning. The microstructure of the polycrystalline films may strongly depend on the type of a substrate. An example shown in Figure 3.
The sacrificial layer must be from the material which has markedly different etching properties than the film pattern. (What does this mean?)
The sacrificial layer must also be a part of the heteroepitaxial system. This means that it must match both the structure of the substrate and the films that are grown on top of it.
NaCl is a good candidate to grow magnetic films with cubic crystal structure. Not so often used because of its higroscopicity.
Procedure for the electron beam evaporation to grow heteroepitaxial structures with NaCl sacrificial layer:
A thin layer of MgO (typically nm) was deposited on MgO substrate to improve the quality of the surface.
NaCl was evaporated at the rate of 0.05 at 350 C
Various magnetic and nonmagnetic transition metal films, such as Fe, Cr, V and Ag, were grown epitaxially on top on NaCl.
This layer dissolves in water.
Zn and Mg are interesting materials for the sacrificial layers because they sublimate in vacuum at relatively low temperatures
Link between the shape and magnetic properties
Angular deposition of Au/Co/Au films resulted in the in-plane magnetic anisotropy of rectangular film patterns. Also changes were observed in the shape of the hysteresis loop and evolution of magnetic domain structure when the film patterns rolled and formed microtubes.
The hysteresis loops of the microtubes with Ni are presented in Figure 5. The magnetic field was applied in two transverse directions. The direction 0 is the direction of the axis of the tubes formed from the patterns and the 90 is transverse to the tubes.
The behavior of the GaFe films, Figure 6, could be interpreted in terms of the shape anisotropy of the microtubes for which the technical magnetization saturation is achieved at lower fields for the field applied along the easy magnetization axis, whereas the loops for the hard direction are tilted and approach saturation magnetization at higher fields. Both type of materials exhibit opposite trends in the change of the coercive field. The coercivity of Ni tubes almost triples for the field applied at 90 while it decreases by about 30% for GaFe films. These facts prove that the change of shape and associated shape anisotropy alone is unable to explain the changes of magnetic properties.

item.title: Genetic Algorithm Example
item.description:
A population is crated (In this case strings). Each string is an individual in the population.
population = [Individual() for _ in 1:POPULATION_SIZE] Copy
Gene pool
Consists of all possible characters that can be used in the strings.
GENES = "letras y caracteres" Copy
Target string
The string we want to evolve our population to match.
TARGET = "Target string" Copy

Each individual's fitness is calculated by comparing its string to the target string.
The fitness score is the number of characters that differ from the target string. The lowest the fitness score, the better the individual.
function cal_fitness(chromosome::Vector{Char}) fitness = 0 for (gs, gt) in zip(chromosome, TARGET) if gs != gt fitness += 1 end end return fitness end Copy

Elitism
The best 10% of the population (individuals with the lowest fitness scores) are carried over to the next generation to ensure that the best solutions are not lost.
s = Int((10 * POPULATION_SIZE)/100) append!(new_generation, population[1:s]) Copy

Mating
The remaining 90% of the new generation is created by mating pairs of individuals from the top 50% of the current population.
Each gene in the offspring's chromosomes is chosen randomly from one of the parents wit a certain probability, or mutated with a small probability to introduce diversity.
function mate(par1::Individual, par2::Individual) child_chromosome = Char[] for (gp1, gp2) in zip(par.chromosome, par2.chromosome) prob = rand() if prob < 0.45 push!(child_chromosome, gp1) elseif prob < 0.90 push!(child_chromosome, gp2) else push!(child_chromosome, mutated_genes()) end end return Individual(child_chromosome, cal_fitness(child_chromosome)) end Copy

Mutated genes
Occasionally, a gene in the offspring's chromosome is replaced with a random gene from the gene pool. This helps maintain a genetic diversity in the population and prevents premature convergence. (This makes it more natural?)
function mutated_genes() return rand(GENES) end Copy

Generation loop
The process of selection, and mutation is repeated for many generations until and individual with a fitness score of 0 is found or a specified number of generations is reached.
generation = 1 found = false while !found population = sort(population, by = x -> x.fitness) #Ascending order if population[1].fitness <= 0 found = true break end new_generation = Vector{Individual}() s = Int((10 * POPULATION_SIZE) / 100) append!(new_generation, population[1:s]) s = Int((90 * POPULATION_SIZE) / 100) for _ in 1:s parent1 = rand(population[1:50]) parent2 = rand(population[1:50]) child = mate(parent1, parent2) push!(new_generation, child) end population = new_generation println("Generation: $generation\tString: ", join(population[1].chromosome), "\tFitness: ", population[1].fitness) generation += 1 end println("Generation: $generation\tString: ", join(population[1].chromosome), "\tFitness: ", population[1].fitness) Copy

item.title: Kepler's Law Quiz
item.description:
What does Kepler's First Law state?
A) Planets move in circular orbits around the Sun.
B) Planets move in elliptical orbits with the Sun at one focus.
C) Planets move in elliptical orbits with the Earth at one focus.
D) Planets move in perfectly straight lines.
According to Kepler's Second Law, which of the following is true about a planet's motion?
A) A planet moves faster when it is farther from the Sun.
B) A planet moves at a constant speed around the Sun.
C) A planet sweeps out equal areas in equal times.
D) A planet moves slower when it is closer to the Sun.
Kepler's Third Law relates which of the following two quantities?
A) The period of a planet's orbit and its distance from the Sun.
B) The speed of a planet and its mass.
C) The eccentricity of the orbit and the distance from the Sun.
D) The mass of the planet and the Sun's gravitational pull.
If a planet takes 8 years to complete one orbit around the Sun, how would Kepler's Third Law predict its average distance from the Sun?
A) 2 Astronomical Units (AU).
B) 4 Astronomical Units (AU).
C) 8 Astronomical Units (AU).
D) 16 Astronomical Units (AU).
Which of Kepler's Laws can explain why Halley's Comet moves much faster when it is near the Sun than when it is far away?
A) Kepler's First Law.
B) Kepler's Second Law.
C) Kepler's Third Law.
D) None of Kepler's Laws.

What does Kepler's First Law state?
Correct Answer: B) Planets move in elliptical orbits with the Sun at one focus.
Explanation: Kepler's First Law, also known as the Law of Ellipses, states that the orbit of a planet around the Sun is not a perfect circle, but an ellipse. The Sun is located at one of the two foci of the ellipse, not at the center.
According to Kepler's Second Law, which of the following is true about a planet's motion?
Correct Answer: C) A planet sweeps out equal areas in equal times.
Explanation: Kepler's Second Law, or the Law of Equal Areas, describes the speed of a planet as it orbits the Sun. When a planet is closer to the Sun, it moves faster, and when it is farther away, it moves slower. The result is that the line connecting the planet to the Sun sweeps out equal areas in equal time intervals, regardless of where the planet is in its orbit.
Kepler's Third Law relates which of the following two quantities?
Correct Answer: A) The period of a planet's orbit and its distance from the Sun.
Explanation: Kepler's Third Law, or the Law of Harmonies, establishes a relationship between the time it takes for a planet to orbit the Sun (its period) and its average distance from the Sun. Mathematically, the square of the orbital period (P²) is proportional to the cube of the semi-major axis of the orbit (a³). In simpler terms, planets that are farther from the Sun take longer to complete an orbit than planets closer to the Sun.
If a planet takes 8 years to complete one orbit around the Sun, how would Kepler's Third Law predict its average distance from the Sun?
Correct Answer: B) 4 Astronomical Units (AU).
Explanation: Using Kepler's Third Law, P2=a3P^2 = a^3P2=a3, we can solve for the semi-major axis (a). If the period P=8P = 8P=8 years, then a3=82=64a^3 = 8^2 = 64a3=82=64, so aaa is the cube root of 64, which is 4. This means the planet's average distance from the Sun is 4 AU (1 AU is the distance from the Earth to the Sun).
Which of Kepler's Laws can explain why Halley's Comet moves much faster when it is near the Sun than when it is far away?
Correct Answer: B) Kepler's Second Law.
Explanation: Kepler's Second Law explains that a comet like Halley's Comet will move much faster when it is near the Sun and much slower when it is farther away. This is because the areas swept out by the comet in equal times must remain equal, and when the comet is near the Sun, it must move quickly to cover the same area as when it is farther away.

item.title: On-Surface Locomotion of Particle Based Microrobots Using Magnetically Induced Oscillation.
item.description:
Fabrication:

Materials: The microrobots consist of microparticles (4.35 µm in diameter) connected in a chain-like manner through magnetic self-assembly using streptavidin-biotin linkages.
Process: Two batches of magnetic microparticles, one with streptavidin coating and the other with biotin coating, are mixed and placed in a magnetic field. The magnetic attraction and chemical bonding result in flexible, chain-like microrobots.
Motion Control Using Magnetic Fields:

System Setup: The control system includes an electromagnetic coil system, bipolar power supplies, a data acquisition device, a computer, an inverted microscope, and a camera.
Field Generation: Near-uniform magnetic fields are generated using coils arranged similarly to Helmholtz coils. The magnetic field strength, direction, and oscillation frequency are controlled to induce the desired microrobot movements.
Oscillatory Swimming Motion:

Mechanism: Microrobots undergo oscillatory motion by manipulating the oscillation angle and frequency. The oscillation generates nonreciprocal motion, enabling propulsion at low Reynolds numbers.
Control Parameters: The control system allows manipulation of the microrobot’s movement direction (angle θ) and speed (oscillation frequency ω).
Velocity Profile:

The microrobots were placed into a PDMS chamber filled with water, and the placed inside the electromagnetic coil system.

item.title: Purcell’s Three-Link Microswimmer Based on IPMC - Simulations in COMSOL Multiphysics
item.description:
Methodology:

Model Development:
COMSOL Multiphysics: A model of the IPMC (Compuestos metalicos de polimeros ionicos) was developed in COMSOL, incorporating both electrostatic and mechanical behavior, and allowing interaction with the surrounding fluid.
Simulation Parameters: The IPMC actuator model in COMSOL offers several advantages, including unrestricted actuator movement, adherence to the Euler-Bernoulli theorem, and fluid interaction dynamics.
Simulation Setup:
Geometry and Mesh: The IPMC was modeled as a sandwich structure with two outer platinum layers and a central nafion polymer layer. The fluid environment was modeled as a rectangular tank.
Physics Definition: The model accounted for ion diffusion dynamics, solid mechanics, fluid-structure interaction, and electrostatic fields.
Validation: The model's accuracy was validated by comparing simulation results with existing literature on IPMC behavior.
Simulation of Purcell’s Swimmer:
Swimmer Configuration: A three-link microswimmer with IPMC lateral links was simulated. The central segment was considered non-deformable for simplifying the convergence of the model.
Movement Primitive: A circular primitive was used to induce non-reciprocal motion, defined by sinusoidal inputs with a phase difference of 90 degrees.
Results:

Movement Analysis: The simulations demonstrated that the IPMC-based swimmer could achieve non-reciprocal motion, resulting in net displacement within the fluid.
Displacement and Velocity: The swimmer's displacement profile showed initial oscillations before reaching a steady-state, with horizontal movement being the primary mode of propulsion.

item.title: Realization of the najafi-golestanian microswimmer.
item.description:
Methodology:

Experimental Setup:
Materials: Ferromagnetic steel spheres (two of 500 µm diameter and one of 397 µm) are used.
Self-Assembly: Spheres self-assemble at an air-water interface due to magnetic and capillary forces, forming a linear configuration when exposed to a vertical magnetic field.
Actuation: Horizontal oscillating magnetic field induces periodic changes in inter-sphere distances, generating propulsion through non-reciprocal deformation.
Model:
Harmonic Oscillators: The microswimmer is modeled as three particles linked by two springs with different natural frequencies, mimicking the magnetocapillary bonds between the spheres.
Equations of Motion: Derived using Newton’s laws, considering forces due to magnetic fields and fluid viscosity.
Experimental Observations:
Swimming Speed: Speed varies with excitation frequency, peaking between 2 and 3 Hz with a maximum speed of ~12 µm/s.
Deformation Cycles: The phase shift between the elongation of the springs is crucial for propulsion, with maximum efficiency when oscillators are in quadrature (90-degree phase shift).
Results:

Speed Profile: The experimental speed profile matches the theoretical model, with speed increasing near the resonant frequency of the oscillators and decreasing at higher frequencies.
Efficiency: Efficiency of propulsion is related to the phase difference and amplitude of oscillator elongations. The model's predictions align well with experimental data.
Scaling: Downscaling the swimmer size suggests potential for effective propulsion even at smaller scales, though practical limits exist due to thermal agitation.

def initial_straight_line_setup(n_of_particles, packing = 0.05, height = 4, radius=1.4):     """     This function returns an array of initial positions of particles in a straight line, and     a region where these particles are enclosed with a packing fraction "packing"     The particles are initially set in a square array, as far from each other as possible.     """     part_in_edge = int(np.round(n_of_particles))     n_of_particles = part_in_edge     print("n_of_particles", n_of_particles)     area_particle = n_of_particles*radius**2*np.pi     print("area particle", area_particle)     area_region = area_particle/packing     print("area region", area_region)     length_region = np.sqrt(area_region)     print("length region", length_region)     part_separation = length_region/part_in_edge     print("part separation", part_separation)     x_loc = np.linspace(         -length_region/2+part_separation/2,         length_region/2-part_separation/2,part_in_edge)     y_loc = 0     [X,Y] = np.meshgrid(x_loc,y_loc)     Z = np.zeros(np.shape(X))     initial_positions = np.array([[x,y,z] for (x,y,z) in zip(X.flatten(),Y.flatten(),Z.flatten())])     if part_separation<2*radius:         raise ValueError("packing is too high")     region = [np.round(length_region),np.round(length_region), height]     return region, initial_positions Copy

item.title: Shape-Programmable Adaptive Multi-Material Microswimmers for Biomedical Applications.
item.description:
En la ultima decada varios micro nadadores de tipo helicoidal son hechos con formas fijas. Estos diseños normalmente de la misma manera tienen propiedades magneticas incorporadas y asi puedan ser controlados via un campo magnetico rotatorio.
Hay una variable muy importante para estos micronadadores y es la viscocidad, la cual puede limitar la velocidad e incluso el movimiento de estos, es por eso que es muy importante crear micronadadores que puedan cambiar su composicion o forma para adaptarse a distintos ambientes.
Actualmente existen micro nadadores que polimeros inteligentes los cuales son capaces de deformar su forma o figura a traves de la estimulacion ambiental tal como la temperatura, pH, y osmolaridad (Es la medida para expresar la concentración total de sustancias en disoluciones usadas en mdedicina). El hidrogel es el más utilizado para micro nadadores por su biocompatibilidad pero estos suelen ser muy fragiles para ser sometidos a otros procesos.

###Diseño asistido por simulación y frabricación del micronadador adaptativo multimaterial.
En general el micronadador tiene tres componentes importantes, incluyendo un principal cuerpo magnetico modelado con un photoresistor SU-8 y microparticulas magneticas )MMPSs=, un cola helicoidal conseguida por hidrogeles de forma adaptativa con regiones modulares suaves y duras (Ahí está el soft matter), y un efector funcional impreso con IP'S para tareas de manipulación.

item.title: Sperm-Shaped Magnetic Microrobots - Fabrication using Electrospinning, Modeling, and Characterization.
item.description:
Fabrication:

Electrospinning Technique: Sperm-shaped microrobots with diameters ranging from 50 µm to 500 µm were fabricated using electrospinning.
Materials: Polystyrene in dimethylformamide mixed with iron oxide nanoparticles was used.
Process: An electrical potential was applied to form a liquid jet, which solidified into beaded fibers. The microrobots were then cut and extracted from these fibers.
Characterization:

Morphology: The microrobots consist of a bead (head) and an ultra-fine fiber (tail), mimicking the morphology of sperm cells.
Magnetic Properties: Iron oxide nanoparticles in the bead provide a magnetic dipole moment, enabling directional control under external magnetic fields.
Movement: The microrobots exhibit planar flagellar waves and flagellated swim when weak (less than 2 mT) oscillating magnetic fields are applied. The average speed was found to be 0.5 body lengths per second at 5 Hz and 1 body length per second at 10 Hz.
Modeling:

Approach: The microrobot's movement was modeled using elastohydrodynamics and Timoshenko-Rayleigh beam theory, showing good agreement with experimental results.

item.title: Symmetries and gaits for purcell's three-link microswimmer model.
item.description:
Methodology:

Symmetry Analysis:
Axial Symmetry: Results in net motion along the longitudinal axis without rotation.
Front-Back Symmetry: Achieves pure rotation or translation without rotation using symmetric gaits.
Shape Trajectory Reflections:
Defined three reflection operators on shape trajectories to analyze finite body motion:
Axial reflection
Front-back reflection
Time-reversal reflection
Symmetric Gaits:
Gait 1: Generates net translation in the x-direction (Purcell’s square gait).
Gait 2: Results in net translation in the y-direction.
Gait 3: Achieves almost pure rotation.
Swimmers with One Symmetry Axis:
Axial Symmetry (Gait 4): Results in pure translation, mostly in the x-direction.
Front-Back Symmetry (Gait 5): Results in pure translation, mostly in the y-direction.
Results:

Numerical Simulations:
Demonstrated the effectiveness of proposed gaits in generating desired motions.
Verified theoretical predictions with simulations showing consistent patterns of motion.
Scaling Analysis:
Provided scaling laws for small-amplitude gaits, showing the dependency of motion on the amplitude of shape changes.
Experimental Validation:

Robotic Prototype:
Conducted experiments with a macro-scale robotic swimmer prototype in a highly viscous fluid.
Results showed qualitative agreement with theoretical predictions, with motion along principal directions as expected.
